Damocles: for the story of Damocles Dav„ in a learned note, quotes Hor. C. iii 1, 17 ; Pers.iii 40; Macr. Somn. Seip. i 10; Philo ap. Eus. Praep. Euang. viii 14, 29; Amm. Marcell. xxix 2, 4.

copias eius, opes: for the asyndeton cf. i 14, 31 11. and Heine, Posen. Progr. p. 8.

Damocle: for the formation of the voc. see ii 21, 4911. on Ulixes.

eadem: the neuter plur. seems (as in i 24, 56: ii 26, 62) to give a more com- prehensive sense than either eandem (Dav. Or.) or eom (Ern. Kl. Ba. Sff.) would have done; cf. Sen. Tro. 1143 (of the dying Polyxena) ‘et sere cuncti magis! Sff. justifies eam by the hypothesis that eadem is due to ditto- graphy of the first syllable of degustare. For the use of degustare here edd. quote Sen. Epp. 33, 5 ‘depone istam spem posse te degustare ingenia summorum hominum'; Quint. iv 1, 14 ‘degustanda tamen haec prooemio non consumenda.’

hominem: more emphatic than eum as m 1 21, 49.
